<hl>
<seg id=1> Hao Ding becomes the first disabled student from a Chinese Orphanage to be accepted into college. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News agency, Hangzhou, September 1st, by Guoxian Zhu, trainee Zhehui Guan- The disabled student Hao Ding, who grew up in Hanzhou Children's Welfare Institution, recently got an acceptance letter from Hanzhou University to study philosophy and social science. </seg>
<seg id=3> It was known that, 19-year-old Hao Ding is the first disabled student from a Children's Welfare Institution to be accepted into college. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> "I really want to jump for joy when I received the letter of acceptance"  Hao Ding said.  However, he was not able to "jump" to express his happiness. </seg>
<seg id=5> When he was three years old he had a high fever and suffered paralysis to his legs and he was accepted to the Children's Welfare Institution. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Hao Ding graduated from the primary school of the Children's Welfare Institution, and then he went to secondary school in the nearby village high school. </seg>
<seg id=7> In the beginning the teachers took him to and from the school everyday.  When he was in eighth grade he started living at the school, only returning to the Children's Welfare Institution on Saturdays.  He never miss a class no matter if it is raining or windy. </seg>
<seg id=8> This year he took the entrance exam and he passed and was accepted by Hanzhou University. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Hao Ding's success combined hard work from all the peoples from all societies. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Children's Welfare Institute gave him care and love for 16 years.  Since last year the Institution spent more than 3,000 yaun on his tuition fees and study materials and nutritious food. </seg>
<seg id=11> People from all societies also gave him helping hands. </seg>
<seg id=12> Hanzhou Nongchang Food Trade Company donated 20,000 Yuan for him to go to college after they learned that he was accepted.  Then a factory that makes wheelchairs and other companies gave him a wheelchair and a cane for walking, etc. </seg>
</p>
